On 5/8/24 at approximately 1130, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 294822 at the hub facility in Anchorage, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consists two plastic jerricans, individually overpacked into fiberboard boxes.  One of the shipments appeared to have a loose closure, resoulting in spillage from the top.  The damaged drum was placed in a salvage drum and the entire shipment is being held, awaiting an amended shipper's declaration for further transport.

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2ft-by-2ft area of the trailer floor and a 5ft-by-10ft area of the concrete lot and estimated that twenty (20) pounds of material was released due to improper loading that punctured four (4) 50-pound plastic bags. Clean Harbors personnel moved all the plastic bags from the pallet to verify only four (4) bags were damaged and then swept up the released material. The damaged bags and recovered material were placed into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums and was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

Doug stated when he arrived at SC143 he saw where something started to leak out of the trailer on to the ground. Doug stated it looked to be 10oz on the payment of the parking lot  and some on the rear bumper of the trailer. Doug opened the trailer doors up and stated the smell was so strong that he had to walk away from the trailer to clean air. Doug stated he does think it is a Hazmat on the trail that is leaking do to the smell coming from the trailer. CURA was called to a ssist with the spill.

column169: XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a product leak at an XPO drop lot. A Contractor determined that the release stemmed from a pinhole size puncture as a result of improper loading on a 55-gallon metal drum. One drum of waste was generated from this incident. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were impacted by this incident.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN2672 Steammate NA1324 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to a 23' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 25' x 10' area of the concrete lot below. The release was caused by the tote falling on its side as a result of improper loading. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbent and vinegar were deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. The impacted absorbents were containerized into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into a cubic yard box. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Driver was delivering gasoline to a gas station.  He brought 4000 gallons divided between multiple pockets of his trailer.  Company policy is to not exceed 90% of a tank's capacity, and upon arrival the driver determined the load would be very close to 90%, so he dropped one pocket at a time, sticking the tank before each pocket, and doing the math to ensure each pocket would fit.  Before dropping 1500 gallons from pocket #3, the driver disconnected the delivery hose to stick the tank.  He obtained the inch reading, converted it to gallons, did the required math, and determined the product in the pocket would fit.  He neglected to re-connect the delivery hose before releasing the product.  He realized his mistake immediately, and stopped the flow of product, but in the very short amount of time (just a few seconds, if that) approximately 51 gallons of product was released to the pavement near the fill.     The driver immediately gathered absorbent materials and pads from his spill kit, and did everything he could to contain the release, but product flowed away from the fill, entering a Central Maine Power (CMP) underground electrical vault.  After stopping the release and containing as much as he could, the driver called our company's 24/7 Safety line to report the spill.  The on-call Safety Manager immediately called 911 and was connected to Westbrook Fire who responded.  He then called Green Site Services for cleanup, and ME DEP who also responded.   When it was determined some quantity of gasoline had entered the electrical vault, the fire department evacuated the area and shut down the street until CMP was able to respond.  Ultimately all liquid was vacuumed out of the vault, a confined space team entered and pressure washed the vault, and speedy dry was applied to all surface material, and was subsequently removed and disposed of properly.  ME DEP was present for the clean-up as well, and approved.
column170: This spill was the result of human error.  One simple, but very important step in the process was missed.  Delivery drivers use the same routine repeatedly, and distraction, stress, or many other factors can result in steps being missed.  All drivers, including the one involved in this delivery, will receive re-training with the focus on slowing down, ensuring accuracy and completion of all steps before commencing deliveries.

column169: XPO-LOGISTICS contacted ERTS regarding a punctured 15-gallon plastic jug of Liquid Laundry Chlorine Bleach. The  container was punctured by a forklift accident. The trailer floor was impacted in an  approximate area of 8’x6’ and the concrete beneath the trailer was impacted in an approximate area of 9’x21’.  A Contractor was dispatched to assist in the clean-up and used oil dry and absorbent pads. Two drums of  waste were generated for disposal that included the overpacked, damaged jug and the impacted absorbents.  No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were impacted by this incident.

column169: During the day sort, the package arrived at the hazmat cage in a bag with suspicions of internal leakage. Drum was placed into a salvage drum to await disposition from PGH.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a battery acid release from a 2113-pound battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of battery acid released to a 6’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and a 30’ x 2’ area of the concrete lot below due to improper loading; the battery fell over in transit. Absorbents and soda ash were worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. All impacted absorbents, pallet pieces, and debris were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged battery was up righted and secured to a pallet. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

When tank car PROX 44601 was in the WLE Brewster Car Shop for routine repairs, the carmen used a gas detection meter to check the top of the car for leaks after noticing an odor coming from the car.  When they inserted the gas meter inside of the protective housing, the gas meter gave an alarm.  They called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the WLE, to come out and look at the car.  I determined that the Vacuum Relief device was leaking around the O Ring Seal.  I have called the car owner to see how they want to proceed with repairs.  As of 5-29-2024, I have not yet heard back from them.
column170: Use a gas detection meter to check valving when securing cars for transportation.

column169: On 5/14/2024, at 1222 hours, personnel in the CSXT Peach Creek Yard, in Logan, WV, discovered CRDX 14064, a loaded hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS SALES, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0514-00151). SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the release was due to a partially open slide gate on the bottom of the hopper car.  CSX Mechanical personnel closed the slide gate and SPSI personnel remediated the product release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Amy James, 803-335-9164). The car was released for transportation.

A Veolia employee was moving containers at the 10 day in-transit storage area with a forklift. The employee needed to move the 951H2 overpack container but due to the issues with utilizing certain drum carts to move these, the employee chose to widen the forks and lift the drum utilizing the edges on the container. Upon lifting with the forks, the container slipped from the forks landing on its side. The employee quickly righted the container with the forklift and tightened the closure, but an estimated 1/2 gallon had leaked out. The 95 gallon overpack contained one 55 gallon drum inside.
column170: Veolia site employees were retrained on the proper closure for the container, and additional equipment to safely move this size/type of container is being investigated.

column169: On 5/21/24, at 1100 hours, FRA Inspector Vincent Au in the CSXT Manville Yard discovered DNAX 130040, Residue tank car UN1993 Flammable Liquid (Acetone, Toluene) with an improperly placed manway gasket, and a vapor release from the vacuum release device.  The railcar was isolated in yard, and National Response Center and New Jersey Department of Environment were notified, report number 24-05-23-1554-22.  The emergency contact number on the waybill was contacted: 877-818-0087, Velocity Emergency Call Service, with Shipper Contact listed as David Solecki from Veolia Inc.  CSX Manager of Hazardous Materials Graham Clark made contact with David Solecki and informed him of situation.  MEI, a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the scene, and found the improperly placed manway gasket and defective vacuum relief device.  MEI corrected the gasket placement, and removed the vacuum relief device, and put a plug in DNAX 130040.  The plug secured the release, and corrective actions were communicated to David Solecki and FRA Inspector Vincent Au.  The tank car has remained held from transportation pending receipt of an OTMA or further repair by certified repair unit.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GME) to remediate the impacted site. GME personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN3149-impacted dock floor and swept them in with hand tools. All damaged containers were set aside and placed into two (2) 55-gallon drums. A Veolia employee arrived at Veolia's ten day intransit facility to prepare for travel to another office for the week when they noticed a large spill in the warehouse.    The employee determined that the spill was from one 55-1A2 open top metal drum containing "UN1325, Waste Flammable Solids, Organic, n.o.s. (Petroleum Hydrocarbons), 4.1, III, RQ (D001)." The leak was traced to a pinhole puncture in the drum. The poor integrity of the container previously went unnoticed because the puncture did not puncture the exterior paint; a blister had formed and kept the liquid from spilling until the blister ruptured. Approximately 5 gallons of liquid was released until the leak stopped on its own over the weekend and was discovered the following morning.  While the employee moved the drum to be overpacked and was taking pictures of the incident, the drum began to leak again from the same blister.   The employee overpacked the drum, put down oil dry to clean the spill, made sure no other drums were also leaking, and contacted management to inform them of the incident.
column170: It's currently unknown what caused the leak. The drum had no obvious signs of damage on the exterior, and the pinhole seemed to be formed from within the drum. Potential causes could be faults in the drum that were not visible from the exterior, or the waste itself causing the pinholes due to potential contaminants, debris, or other components of the waste material.

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding two damaged 55-gallon steel drums containing hazardous product, H.B.  Fuller 14216.One drum was punctured by a forklift and the other was damaged when trying to move it away  from the punctured drum. A Contractor was called to overpack both drums. The Contractor advised that an  estimated 25-gallons of product released onto the wooden trailer floor and the concrete beneath the trailer. The  trailer floor was impacted in a 15’x8.5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer was impacted in a 10’x 10’ area. The Contractor used oil dry, absorbent pads, and booms to contain and clean-up the release. Two  additional drums of waste were generated for the impacted clean-up debris. No storm-drains, waterways, or  soil were affected by this incident.

On May 24, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN1170 was dropped and released approximately four (4) gallons of product to the concrete and soil. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SMR Rapid Response, LLC (SMR) to remediate the impacted site. RLC advised the CES incident manager that all remediation and disposal would be completed by personnel at the customer location. SMR was advised to stand down as no further action would be needed. Photos were taken to document the scene and SMR personnel noted no further actions required on-site and demobilized.

XPO Logistics terminal USU experienced a UN1198 Formaldehyde Solution 37% 14% release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately all 55-gallons of material released to the trailer and dock floor in a 1’ x 200’ area and a 10’ x 10’ area due to a forklift puncture. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then deployed to collect all free liquids. A pressure washer was utilized to further clean the impacted doc area and all wastewater was solidified with absorbents. The impacted absorbents and PPE used were then collected and containerized into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On May 14th, the owner of Oregon Valley Farms, Josh, came into the front counter to personally drop off some of these shipments.  Previously the station had discovered undeclared shipments that were of similar packages He told the counter agent that he had changed his process that there would be no liquid nitrogen in the package when shipped. After Josh left a visual inspection of the packages he dropped off was done and one hadhad visible frost on the outside of the package. The package was opened up and as suspected there was liquid nitrogen in the package. There was a significant amount of vapor coming out of the package and as the vapor settled liquid nitrogen in the bottom of the package. was visible.   The package is being held pending disposition.

XPO Logistics terminal NBM experienced a UN2693 Chemtron De-Ox release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon product released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the wood trailer floor due to a crack on the top corner of the tote. Soda ash and absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area to clean and neutralize the release. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal XML experienced a UN3267 WT680 Precipitant release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 ounces of product released to a 0.5’ x 0.5’ area of the trailer floor and top of the drum due to a loose bung. The impacted areas were cleaned with citric acid solution and absorbent pads to clean and neutralize the material. The bung cap was resecured, and a slosh test was conducted for the drum to continue in transport. The impacted pads were containerized into a 30-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column169: On May 8, 2024 at 1800 Mechanical personnel in the Conrail Port Reading Yard discovered , HSRX 3130 a loaded tank car of Petroleum Distillates (Isomerate) leaking from the top of the tank car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Kinder Morgan was notified directly via phone . Conrail Manager of  Hazardous Material, Joe Caccamo along with Marion Environmental personnel, investigated the leak and found  the source be from the reclosing pressure relief device. Liquid product was escaping from the PRD indicating an overloaded condition. The magnetic gauging device was completely maxed out and showing no vapor space in the tank car. A vacuum truck was used to safely remove approximately 3500 gallons.  Cause Code: 419 5 x ( 5 + 5 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 100

As freight was being moved on the dock of the destination terminal, a forklift operator's fork made contact with this drum, causing puncture and a release of material. The drum was immediately turned onto it's side and placed into an overpack container to prevent further release. The released material was neutralized and absorbed. Due to the material being hazardous, the packaging specifications were not able to be safely obtained.
column170: The employee responsible for the container damage was counselled per company policy regarding proper forklift operating procedures. This incident may be used in future dock safety topics to illustrate the importance of proper forklift operating procedures.

column169: GATX 6351 was found to be leaking liquid from the top of the car. Upon investigation by a responder, it was noted that the leak was coming from the liquid line cap. The pressure was relieved from the car to stop the release. The liquid cap was removed and inspected for the gasket, which was present. The cap was then tightened and all other plugs/valves/nuts checked for tightness. The car and ground were cleaned by a contractor.
column170: The shipper must ensure that all caps/plugs are properly tightened and secured to prevent future releases of hazardous materials.(NAR:249)

XPO-LOGISTICS contacted ERTS regarding a leaking lid on a 55-gallon poly drum containing SaniDate 5.0. The lid  appeared to be not sealed tight enough or not sealed correctly. This resulted in an estimated 1-cup release of product onto the top of the poly drum, the plastic shrink-wrap, and cardboard. A Contractor removed the  impacted plastic shrink wrap and cardboard and submerged them in water. The leaking drum was overpacked into a 95-gallon DF. In total, 2 drums of waste were generated for disposal. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil  were impacted by this incident.

column169: On 5/19/2024 at approximately 1845, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 906768 at the ramp facilty in Denver, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods commodity.  The shipment consisted of one sealed lead acid battery, packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered showing evidence of spillage. The acid spilled from the battery, however the cause of the spillage is unknown. One employee was reported burned from the acid spillage and was treated with first aid.  It does not appear that the commodity was properly identified nor declared as a sealed lead acid battery.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.
